This is evidentlyaddressed to archbishop Arundel. The comet referred to is no doubt that of March, 1402. The evils complained of are the conspiracies against the king, and we are told by the chroniclers that the appearance of this comet in the north was taken as a presage of the troubles in Wales and in Northumberlandt cp. Walsingham‚ ii. 248. Adam of Usk, who saw it when on the Continent, says it was visible by day as well as by night, and that it probably prefigured the death of the duke of Milan, whose arms were also seen in the sky (p. 73).

5. The neglect complained of is of prayers for the soul of the departed. Gower seems to have followed his own precept and made arrangements for some of the prayers in his lifetirne, though others are provided for by his will. Berthelette in his preface to the Confessio A mantis (15 32) speaks of Gower’s place of burial as having been prepared by himself in the church of St. Mary OvereS, ‘ where he hath of his owne foundation a masse dayly songe. And more ouer he hath an obyte yerely done for hym within the same churche, on fryday aster the feaste of the blessed pope saynte Gregory.’ St. Gregory’s day is March 12.
